Ines Robles presented the [ROLL Interim Meeting](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/interim-2026-roll-01/materials/slides-interim-2026-roll-01-sessa-roll-interim-meeting-02) slides. 

*   **RFC Updates:** Three new RFCs were recently published (RPL, NSF, and DAO projection).
*   **Milestone Updates:**
    *   **July 2026:** Submit enrollment priority draft.
    *   **October 2026:** Submit `draft-ietf-roll-dis-modifications`.
    *   **November 2026:** Submit `draft-ietf-roll-nsa-extension`.
    *   **December 2026:** Recharter or close the working group.
*   **Capabilities & MoPs:** Due to lack of feedback and resources, these items have been deferred for future work and removed from the active milestones.

### 2. Enrollment Priority Draft - Review of GitHub Issues
Ines Robles and Michael Richardson reviewed outstanding GitHub issues based on reviewer feedback:

*   **Issue 37 (References):** Normative and informative references have been cleaned up and corrected by Michael Richardson.
*   **IANA Registry Link:** Michael Richardson will update the IANA section to explicitly specify the registry links.
*   **Privacy Considerations:** Michael Richardson deleted this section as there are no distinct privacy implications.
*   **Operational Considerations & Default Constants:** Discussion arose regarding why the default priority value is set to 40 and whether it should be operator-configurable. Michael Richardson explained that making this configurable defeats the "zero-touch" goal of the protocol, as it would require out-of-band configuration. Remous-Aris Koutsiamanis suggested adding a sentence explaining that constants are intentionally non-configurable to aid zero-touch deployment. Michael Richardson agreed to add this clarification.
*   **Terminology (Telemetry):** A reviewer questioned the use of the word "telemetry." Michael Richardson defended the term, noting its standard usage within the IETF (e.g., RFC 9232) and in general dictionary definitions, and opted to keep it.
*   **Issue 42 (Secure Enrollment title):** Michael Richardson removed the word "secure" from the title/text where appropriate to avoid confusion.
*   **RPL Capabilities and T Bit:** 
    *   The section on RPL capabilities will be removed since capabilities work is deferred.
    *   For the T bit (which triggers a trickle reset), the requirement will be changed from a "should" to a "must" to guarantee a trickle reset occurs when setting the bit.

### 3. Enrollment Priority: Lollipop Counter & 6LR Propagation
Michael Richardson led a technical discussion on propagation rules using the slide deck [Enrollment Priority Problem Text (v2)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/interim-2026-roll-01/materials/slides-interim-2026-roll-01-sessa-enrollment-priority-problem-text-01).

*   **The Problem:** The current draft text states that 6LRs "must not change the option when propagating it." Michael Richardson pointed out that this contradicts the purpose of adding the lollipop counter, which was introduced to handle priority updates as they propagate down the DODAG. If 6LRs cannot change the option, the priority values cannot increment, rendering the mechanism ineffective.
*   **Technical Analysis:**
    *   A value of `7F` (hex) represents infinity/off, signaling that enrollment is disabled.
    *   If enrollment is enabled, priority values must increment as they propagate down the rank to reflect path cost/congestion. This allows prospective joiners to select optimal paths (e.g., choosing a parent announcing a priority of `52` over one announcing `7F` or `72`).
    *   Pascal Thubert agreed that the restriction against 6LRs modifying the option was a legacy text error from before the lollipop counter was introduced.
*   **The Solution:** The group agreed that 6LRs must be allowed to increment the priority value as it propagates down the DODAG (up to the maximum of `7F`).
*   **Parent Selection Rule:** Pascal Thubert noted that when a node has multiple parents, it must propagate the value associated with its preferred parent. Michael Richardson agreed and will add this rule to the text.

